english:
  title: Carnation
  author: Jeong Seup-myeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The world loves the crimson peony,
    filling courtyards with its planted pride.
    But who knows in the wild grasslands,
    among rough and barren fields,
    there too bloom flowers of grace?

    Their petals glow like moonlight on village ponds,
    their fragrance drifts on mountain winds.
    In this remote and humble place,
    where few young nobles venture,
    their delicate beauty belongs
    to the farmer's weathered eye alone.
  footnotes:
    - The stone carnation (石竹) was traditionally considered a humble flower compared to the peony, making it a fitting subject for a poem about overlooked beauty and rural virtue.
    - The contrast between the cultivated peony of urban society and the wild carnation of the countryside reflects broader themes in East Asian poetry about simplicity versus excess.
